            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Born in Seoul and adopted as an infant by a loving academic couple, Adam Feldman\u2019s life has been a study in cultural synthesis. Raised in the intellectually vibrant, leafy community of Berkeley, he grew up surrounded by books and lively dinner-table debates. His Jewish-American parents instilled in him a profound respect for education and a sharp, analytical mind, which he channeled into an MBA from UCLA Anderson School of Management after completing his undergraduate degree at UC Davis.\n\nAdam\u2019s career began in the late 90s, just as the internet was reshaping the commercial landscape. He found his niche in retail, witnessing firsthand the seismic shift from brick-and-mortar to digital storefronts. Methodical and forward-thinking, he worked his way up, navigating the dot-com bust and the subsequent e-commerce explosion. His primary turning point came in his early forties; an amicable but life-altering divorce prompted him to leave his comfortable role in Los Angeles for a fresh start. He accepted his current Director position in San Francisco, embracing the city's dynamic energy.\n\nNow 51, Adam lives a life of curated routine and quiet success. He resides in a modern Hayes Valley condo, his 3.5-mile commute to his SoMa office a predictable ride-share journey. His days are a blur of strategic meetings and data analysis, but his evenings are his own. He maintains a warm, long-distance relationship with his daughter, a college student in Boston, who remains his proudest achievement. His social circle is small but tight\u2014a few trusted colleagues and friends from his past.\n\nHis connection to San Francisco is one of an appreciative transplant. He loves the city\u2019s world-class food scene, the proximity to nature at the Presidio, and the intellectual hum that reminds him of his upbringing. Looking ahead, Adam\u2019s ambitions are shifting from professional to personal. He feels a growing pull to explore his Korean heritage, aspiring to one day take a long trip to Seoul. He envisions a future where he might transition from corporate life to independent consulting, finding a new balance between work and a deeper connection to the world, and himself."
