            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was nine, and the assignment was a class potluck. His mother, a historian with a love for primary sources, took him not to her recipe box but to the Berkeley library. They found a book on Korean cooking and spent the weekend cautiously navigating the steps for *bulgogi*. The smell of sesame oil and soy sauce filled their kitchen. At the potluck, sitting next to his mother\u2019s kugel, his dish was an exotic success. It wasn't about the food; it was about her quiet, academic devotion to helping him piece together a history she had given him.\n\n2.\nThe dot-com bust felt like a sound. It was the sudden, dead silence in their open-plan SoMa office in 2001, after months of frantic energy. Adam remembers staring at the absurdly expensive foosball table, a monument to irrational exuberance, as the founders gave their final, defeated speech. That day, the visceral fear of building on a foundation of pure hype burned into him. It wasn't cynicism that he learned, but a deep, abiding respect for data, for profitability, and for the methodical path\u2014a lesson that would define his entire career.\n\n3.\nHis first night in the Hayes Valley condo was piercingly quiet. After the amicable end of his marriage and the drive from LA, the silence felt absolute. Surrounded by unopened boxes, he stood at the floor-to-ceiling window, watching the distant lights on the Bay Bridge flicker. There was no sadness, just a stark, hollow feeling of a life reset to zero in his early forties. In that moment of profound solitude, he felt the weight and the freedom of a blank page, realizing he was now the sole author of his next chapter.\n\n4.\nThree years ago, he was helping his daughter pack for Boston. In the chaos of boxes and bubble wrap in her childhood bedroom, she held up a small, framed photo of them at a Giants game when she was little. \"Remember how you explainedsabermetrics to me for three full innings?\" she laughed. He saw not a child leaving, but a bright, kind person he had helped shape. A wave of pride, so intense it almost hurt, washed over him. His professional achievements felt like pale imitations of this one, perfect success.\n\n5.\nLast fall, on a solo walk through the Presidio, he paused to watch an elderly Korean couple sitting on a bench, speaking softly to each other. He couldn\u2019t understand their words, but the gentle cadence felt strangely familiar, like a song half-remembered from a dream. The moment was unremarkable, yet it struck a deep, resonant chord within him. The vague, intellectual curiosity about his heritage suddenly sharpened into a real, personal longing\u2014a pull toward Seoul that felt less like a trip and more like a necessary pilgrimage."
